# Immutable Entity Pattern Context

Use this mini convention for write-side entities.

## Rules

- Write-side entities must be immutable.
- Entity state must be readonly after construction.
- State transitions must return a new entity instance.
- Do not mutate entity properties in place.
- Use pure methods for behavioral transitions when possible.
- Keep invariant checks inside entity factory or transition methods.
- Every entity must call `Object.freeze(this)` at the end of its private constructor.
- Missing `Object.freeze(this)` in a private constructor is forbidden.

Required constructor pattern:

```ts
private constructor(params: ReconstructParams) {
  this.id = params.id;
  // ... assign all fields ...
  Object.freeze(this);
}
```

## Recommended Shape

- Use a private constructor and static factory methods.
- Use readonly fields and defensive copies for nested objects.
- Expose transition methods that return a new entity and emitted events when applicable.

## TypeScript Example

```ts
/** Domain identifier value for a CI entity. */
export type CiId = string;

/** Domain events emitted by CI write-side transitions. */
export type CiDomainEvent =
  | {
      readonly type: "CiCreated";
      readonly payload: {
        readonly id: CiId;
        readonly name: string;
        readonly classId: string;
        readonly occurredAt: Date;
      };
    }
  | {
      readonly type: "CiRenamed";
      readonly payload: {
        readonly id: CiId;
        readonly previousName: string;
        readonly name: string;
        readonly occurredAt: Date;
      };
    };

/** Immutable state container for CI entity transitions. */
export type CiState = {
  readonly id: CiId;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly classId: string;
  readonly updatedAt: Date;
};

/** Immutable write-side entity for Configuration Item domain logic. */
export class CiEntity {
  private constructor(
    private readonly state: CiState,
    private readonly pendingEvents: readonly CiDomainEvent[] = [],
  ) {}

  /** Factory method with invariant validation and event emission. */
  public static create(input: {
    id: CiId;
    name: string;
    classId: string;
    now: Date;
  }): CiEntity {
    if (input.name.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new Error("CI name must not be empty");
    }

    const createdEvent: CiDomainEvent =
      {
        type: "CiCreated",
        payload: {
          id: input.id,
          name: input.name,
          classId: input.classId,
          occurredAt: input.now,
        },
      };

    return new CiEntity(
      {
        id: input.id,
        name: input.name,
        classId: input.classId,
        updatedAt: input.now,
      },
      [createdEvent],
    );
  }

  /** Transition method that returns a new immutable instance and emitted events. */
  public rename(params: {
    name: string;
    now: Date;
  }): CiEntity {
    if (params.name.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new Error("CI name must not be empty");
    }

    const renamedEvent: CiDomainEvent = {
      type: "CiRenamed",
      payload: {
        id: this.state.id,
        previousName: this.state.name,
        name: params.name,
        occurredAt: params.now,
      },
    };

    return new CiEntity({
      ...this.state,
      name: params.name,
      updatedAt: params.now,
    }, [...this.pendingEvents, renamedEvent]);
  }

  /** Returns pending events without clearing them. */
  public getPendingEvents(): readonly CiDomainEvent[] {
    return [...this.pendingEvents];
  }

  /** Returns a new entity instance with cleared pending events. */
  public clearPendingEvents(): CiEntity {
    return new CiEntity({ ...this.state }, []);
  }

  /** Read-only projection of current entity state. */
  public toState(): CiState {
    return { ...this.state };
  }
}
```

Event impact explained:

- Immutability makes each state transition explicit.
- Each transition can return both the new entity and the domain events to publish.
- Command handlers can persist the new state and forward emitted events to the outbox/publisher.

Internal event pattern:

```ts
let entity = CiEntity.create({
  id: "ci-1",
  name: "api-gateway",
  classId: "class-service",
  now: new Date(),
});

entity = entity.rename({
  name: "api-gateway-v2",
  now: new Date(),
});

const events = entity.getPendingEvents();

// Persist entity state, then publish events.
// After successful publish:
entity = entity.clearPendingEvents();
```

Important:

- Keep event retrieval and clearing explicit in command handlers.
- Clear pending events only after successful persist/publish workflow.
- Domain events must be as atomic as practical: prefer one business-significant field change per event, and avoid bundling multiple field mutations unless a functional constraint requires them to stay coupled.

## Anti-Pattern

Avoid mutable updates such as:

- Reassigning entity properties directly.
- Exposing public setters.
- Returning void from state-changing methods.

## Integration Notes

- Keep DTO contracts in BC types package.
- Map DTOs to immutable entities in command handlers or domain services.
- Persist resulting immutable state through write repository adapters.
